    "created_at": "2014-06-17T01:08:06Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-06-17T01:08:06Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I don't think we should try to be too clever with our imports, because that kind of thing breaks static analysis tools. E.g. in my IDE, I can ctrl+click on a name to go to the definition - that's not going to work if we're messing around with imports.\n\nHonestly, I suspect we're over-focussing on a problem that primarily affects us, and other people who live on master. All the people installing IPython releases through conda, pip, distro packaging tools, etc. will get dependencies automatically.\n\nEven for the people who do live on master, a. this only happens once every few months, it's not the end of the world, and b. those people can probably work out that `ImportError: no module named foo` means they need to go and install foo.\n"
  },
