    "created_at": "2014-06-17T01:57:38Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-06-17T01:57:38Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "But:\n- If we're not hiding the traceback, the long, daunting error message is still there, so it's not really friendly.\n- After people have seen this a few times, they will start to treat it like any other import error, because we can't tell whether an import failed because a module wasn't installed, or because there's some other problem. We can't even tell if it's that import that failed, or something else that was imported by that module. If the user sees \"blah blah blah ImportError: foo ... IPython depends on the bar package, please install it first\", we're obscuring the real problem.\n\nI don't really think it's worth cluttering up every external import with a dozen extra lines of exception handling for a slightly better error message in a fairly rare case that we can't reliably detect anyway. And trying to have clever machinery to do it without those dozen extra lines would be even worse.\n"
  },
