    "created_at": "2014-06-17T06:30:24Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-06-17T06:30:24Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I also think this is treating the symptoms instead of curing the disease. \nIMHO IPython should refuse to launch a subapp if it has not been installed correctly with pip install Ipython [whatever].\n\nWe know that we want notebook and other frontends as separate package. Why not publishing a dummy (for now) ipython-notebook package.\nRequire it, and fail with an usefull error message if this module does not import?\n\nThen we can be pretty certain that Ipython was not installed correctly.\n\nImport traceback are what they are, they should not be messed with. 95+% of user will not even bother to read the extra line you added. If you want a message of hope instead, please supress the trace back and add the option of --debug showing it again.\n\nEnvoyÃ© de mon iPhone\n\n> Le 17 juin 2014 Ã  07:46, Paul Ivanov notifications@github.com a Ã©crit :\n> \n> The long and daunting message ends on a message of hope: install jsonschema and all will be well.\n> \n> I hear your concern @takluyver about cluttering every external import, but that's not what this PR proposes. If this starts to get treated like a regular import error (which it is) then there's no information lost and we're not introducing any kind of unmanageable complexity to make this happen.\n> \n> @fperez bumped into this, I bumped into this, as did @pmarshwx over in #5979.\n> \n> As @minrk pointed out, we already do these kinds of messages for pyzmq and tornado. Between folks running off of master and pip installing ipython without the square brackets optional dependencies, enough developers can get tripped up by this particular import error down the line that it's worth addressing.\n> \n> â€”\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub.\n"
